    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="573"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d573">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.00244/140</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mallet</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="96" xml:id="d573fn96">By note dated September 28, 1936, the Secretary
                        of State acknowledged receipt of this communication.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 305</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-21">September 21,
                            1936</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honour to inform you, on the
                    instructions of His Majesty’s Principal Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs,
                    that the <pb facs="0811" n="731" xml:id="pg_731"/> attention of His Majesty’s
                    Government has been drawn to the terms of the Act—Public No. 755—74th Congress
                    which was approved on the 22nd June last,<note n="97" xml:id="d573fn97">49 Stat.
                        1820.</note> defining the jurisdiction of the United States coastguards.</p>
                <p>2. It is observed that under the terms of the Bill United States coastguards are
                    authorized “at any time to go on board of any vessel, subject to the
                    jurisdiction, or to the operation of any law, of the United States, to address
                    enquiries to those on board, to examine ships’ documents and papers, and to
                    examine, inspect and search the vessel and use all necessary force to compel
                    compliance.” In order to avoid the possibility of any misunderstanding I have
                    been instructed to place on record that His Majesty’s Government in the United
                    Kingdom cannot recognize the right of the United States authorities to exercise
                    any of the powers in question outside territorial waters proper over any vessel
                    flying the British flag, except as provided for by the Convention between the
                    United Kingdom and the United States of January 23rd, 1924.<note n="98"
                        xml:id="d573fn98">
                        <ref target="frus1924v01#pg_158">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1924, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 158</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">V. A. L. Mallet</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
